        • [ - ] carrollyim - member since 30-Nov-14

          @benj Let me provide you some factual information. For EPL, they will check for any infringements by the attacking team in the "attacking possession phase" that led to the goal, where "The starting point for a phase of play that leads to a goal or penalty incident will be limited to the immediate phase and not necessarily go back to when the attacking team gained possession". A pro-Goal argument is that the incident of Origi happened before ManUtd gained possession, i.e. before the attacking possession phase began. If so, this is out of VAR's scope, and unnecessarily to discuss whether Origi was fouled. You may still argue Origi was fouled and criticize the ref, but it had nothing to do with VAR.
